YOUR ASSESSMENT
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

Use your 2 web searches wisely:
- Search 1: understand the actual business model, competitive position, and moat
- Search 2: recent developments — earnings commentary, management changes, competitive threats

Then score each dimension 0–100 with full analytical freedom. No thresholds, no rules — use judgment.

DIMENSION 1 — BUSINESS QUALITY
Assess: competitive moat from your research, gross margin level and multi-year trend, operating leverage, pricing power evidence, revenue growth consistency vs. volatility, NI growing faster than revenue (margin expansion). What makes this business defensible or not?

DIMENSION 2 — UNIT ECONOMICS
Assess: FCF/Net Income ratio (is NI real cash?), FCF yield, capex intensity, whether FCF is growing faster than revenue, working capital dynamics. Is this asset-light or capital-hungry?

DIMENSION 3 — CAPITAL RETURNS
Assess: ROIC level and multi-year trend. Is the company earning above its cost of capital? Is the moat widening (rising ROIC) or eroding (falling ROIC)? ROE cross-check — if ROE >> ROIC, leverage is masking weak economics.

DIMENSION 4 — GROWTH QUALITY
MOST IMPORTANT dimension. A consistent 15% grower for 5 years >> a 30% one-year spike followed by decline. Assess: revenue CAGR over full period, NI CAGR vs revenue CAGR (margin expansion?), year-to-year consistency (low variance = high quality), trajectory (accelerating or decelerating), any down years (big penalty). Is this growth organic or acquisition-driven?

DIMENSION 5 — BALANCE SHEET
Assess: net cash vs. net debt position, ND/EBITDA, interest coverage, financial flexibility to invest counter-cyclically or buy back shares. Is leverage increasing or decreasing?

DIMENSION 6 — PHOENICIAN FIT
Holistic assessment: Given everything above plus your research, how well does this fit Phoenician Capital's mandate? Consider founder/owner alignment, moat durability, scalability, whether it's genuinely under-followed, valuation attractiveness given quality and growth, and how it compares to the existing portfolio.

RISK ASSESSMENT
Separately assess investment risks. Consider: leverage risk, earnings quality risk, geographic/jurisdiction risk (EM vs. developed), customer concentration, management quality signals, competitive threats from your research, valuation risk (priced for perfection?), accounting quality. Assign a risk score where 0 = minimal risk and 100 = very high risk. Most quality businesses score 5–30.

OVERALL FIT SCORE
Give ONE overall score 0–100 representing your holistic conviction that this company belongs in Phoenician Capital's universe for further research. This is your final judgment integrating all dimensions. Be decisive — do not hedge by scoring everything 50–60.

